    </style></head><body><div id="main"><h1>JEP draft: Linux/musl libc Port</h1><table class="head"><tr><td>Owner</td><td>Aleksei Voitylov</td></tr><tr><td>Type</td><td>Feature</td></tr><tr><td>Scope</td><td>Implementation</td></tr><tr><td>Status</td><td>Draft</td></tr><tr><td>Component</td><td>hotspot&#8201;/&#8201;runtime</td></tr><tr><td>Discussion</td><td>portola dash dev at openjdk dot java dot net</td></tr><tr><td>Effort</td><td>M</td></tr><tr><td>Duration</td><td>M</td></tr><tr><td>Created</td><td>2019/08/13 10:33</td></tr><tr><td>Updated</td><td>2019/08/13 21:33</td></tr><tr><td>Issue</td><td><a href="https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8229469">8229469</a></td></tr></table><div class="markdown"><h2 id="Summary">Summary</h2>
<p>Port JDK to Linux/musl libc and enable JDK on Alpine Linux x86_64.</p>
<h2 id="Motivation">Motivation</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.musl-libc.org/">Musl libc</a> is an implementation of the standard library functionality described in the ISO C and POSIX standards intended for Linux-based systems. Several Linux distributions including <a href="https://alpinelinux.org/">Alpine Linux</a> are based on musl libc and others provide optional musl package, e.g. <a href="https://openwrt.org/">OpenWrt</a> and <a href="https://www.archlinux.org/">Arch Linux</a>.</p>
<p>Alpine Linux distribution is widely adopted in cloud deployments, microservices and container environments due to small image size (under 6 MB for Docker <a href="https://hub.docker.com/_/alpine">base image</a>). Enabling Java to run out of the box on such deployments will naturally allow Tomcat, Jetty, Spring and other popular frameworks to eventually support such platforms natively.</p>
<p>By additionally using jlink to further reduce the size of the Runtime a user would be able to create a smaller Runtime targeted to run a specific application. The set of modules required by an application can be determined by jdeps command. For example, if a target application only depends on java.base module, base Docker image with Alpine Linux and a Runtime with java.base module and Server VM would fit in 38 MB.</p>
<p>The same motivation applies to Embedded deployments where size constraint is also an issue.</p>
<h2 id="Description">Description</h2>
<p>This JEP intends to integrate the <a href="https://openjdk.java.net/projects/portola/">Portola Project</a> upstream. The Portola Project is led by Oracle and contains patches from several external contributors. Several OpenJDK support vendors (Azul, BellSoft) have been shipping production-ready binaries with musl libc support for LTS releases which justifies the demand and maturity of the musl libc port. The intent is to continue supporting it going forward once the code is integrated upstream.</p>
<h2 id="Alternatives">Alternatives</h2>
<p>Keep the musl libc port downstream in Portola project.</p>
<h2 id="Testing">Testing</h2>
<ul>
<li>To ensure absence of regressions on regular platforms JCK and JTreg will be run on GLIBC-based Linux (x86, AArch64, ARM), Windows, Mac and Solaris (x86, SPARC) before integration</li>
<li>
<pre><code>The quality of the musl port code will be verified by running relevant subset of JTreg on Alpine Linux. A downport of Portola to a current production JDK release will be ensured to pass JCK</code></pre>
</li>
<li>A new check for musl will be introduced in VMProps.java which will enable to create a subset of JTreg tests suitable for musl (vm.musl test group).</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="Risks-and-Assumptions">Risks and Assumptions</h2>
<ul>
<li>This port requires point changes to shared code base (build system, hostpot, libnet, libjava, libjli and libawt).</li>
<li>HotSpot Serviceability Agent Attach functionality will be disabled in musl libc port.</li>
<li>Musl libc port for non-x86 architectures will be done in a follow-up enhancement once Alpine Linux support on such platforms is in demand.</li>
</ul>
